stopifnot(is(bcb, "bcbioRNASeq"))
invisible(validObject(bcb))

Overview

  • Principal Investigator: Kevin Eggan
  • Researcher: Joseph Klim
  • Experiment: ES-derived motor neuron knockdown RNA-seq

For the differential expression analysis, we used DESeq2 1.18.1. We employed a design formula (~date + category) that accounts for the date batch effect. For more information on design formulas in DESeq2, run help("design", "DESeq2") in R.

Here were discarding the NoTx samples from the analysis. Note that since these 3 samples have been dropped, the values of the normalized counts will change, since were now only looking at 15 samples. Ive uploaded these updated counts into the results/ directory.

> dds <- bcbio(bcb, "DESeqDataSet")
> dim(dds)
> 
> # Drop the `NoTx_*` samples from the analysis
> keep_samples <- colnames(dds)[which(!is.na(dds$treatment))]
> keep_samples
> 
> dds <- selectSamples(dds, sampleID = keep_samples)
> dim(dds)
> colnames(dds)
> 
> # Now set the design formula and run DESeq
> design(dds) <- params$design
> dds <- DESeq(dds)
> rld <- rlog(dds)

Since the dimensions of the dataset have changed, we need to resave the normalized counts.

> normalized_counts <- counts(dds, normalized = TRUE)
> writeCounts(normalized_counts, dir = file.path("results", "counts"))
> saveData(dds, normalized_counts, rld, dir = data_dir)
> dropbox_normalized_counts_resave <- copyToDropbox(c(normalized_counts = file.path("results", 
+     "counts", "normalized_counts.csv.gz")), dir = params$dropbox_dir)

Alpha level (FDR) cutoffs

Lets take a look at the number of genes we get with different false discovery rate (FDR) cutoffs. These tests subset P values that have been multiple test corrected using the Benjamini Hochberg (BH) method (Benjamini and Hochberg 1995).

> alphaSummary(dds)
0.1 0.05 0.01 0.001 1e-06
LFC > 0 (up) 749, 1.8% 493, 1.2% 225, 0.53% 95, 0.22% 38, 0.089%
LFC < 0 (down) 607, 1.4% 392, 0.92% 177, 0.42% 69, 0.16% 25, 0.059%
outliers 67, 0.16% 67, 0.16% 67, 0.16% 67, 0.16% 67, 0.16%
low counts 24298, 57% 24298, 57% 23489, 55% 23489, 55% 23489, 55%
cutoff (mean count < 10) (mean count < 10) (mean count < 8) (mean count < 8) (mean count < 8)

Results

> # help('results', 'DESeq2') For contrast argument as character vector: 1.
> # Design matrix factor of interest.  2. Numerator for LFC (expt).  3.
> # Denominator for LFC (control).
> res_unshrunken <- results(dds, contrast = params$contrast, alpha = params$alpha)
> 
> # DESeqResults with shrunken log2 fold changes (LFC) help('lfcShrink',
> # 'DESeq2')
> res_shrunken <- lfcShrink(dds = dds, contrast = params$contrast, res = res_unshrunken)
> 
> # Use shrunken LFC values by default
> res <- res_shrunken
> saveData(res, res_shrunken, res_unshrunken, dir = data_dir)

We performed the analysis using a BH adjusted P value cutoff of 0.05 and a log fold-change (LFC) ratio cutoff of 0.

Plots

Were seeing a small but consistent effect size. Based on these results, I dont recommend applying a log fold change cutoff to our list of differentially expressed genes.

Mean average (MA)

An MA plot compares transformed counts on M (log ratio) and A (mean average) scales (Y. H. Yang et al. 2002).

> markdownHeader("shrunken", level = 3)

shrunken

> plotMA(res_shrunken)

> markdownHeader("unshrunken", level = 3)

unshrunken

> plotMA(res_unshrunken)

Volcano

A volcano plot compares significance (BH-adjusted P value) against fold change (log2) (Cui and Churchill 2003; Li et al. 2014). Genes in the green box with text labels have an adjusted P value are likely to be the top candidate genes of interest.

> markdownHeader("labeled", level = 3)

labeled

> plotVolcano(res, lfc = params$lfc, gene2symbol = gene2symbol(bcb), ntop = 20, 
+     histograms = TRUE)

Heatmap

This plot shows only differentially expressed genes on a per-sample basis. We have scaled the data by row and used the ward.D2 method for clustering (Ward 1963).

> # help('pheatmap', 'pheatmap')
> annotation_col <- colData(dds) %>% .[, c("category", "treatment", "date"), drop = FALSE] %>% 
+     as.data.frame()
> plotDEGHeatmap(res, counts = rld, gene2symbol = gene2symbol(bcb), annotationCol = annotation_col, 
+     clustering_method = "ward.D2")

DEG PCA plots

Now performing PCA using only our list of DEGs, we can see the samples are separating by treatment on PC1, which is good to see. The samples are separating on PC2 by date (batch), but thats okay because weve taken that into account in our DESeq model for performing the differential expression. This looks good.

> markdownHeader("category", level = 2)

> plotDEGPCA(res, counts = rld, interestingGroups = "category")

> markdownHeader("category:date", level = 2)

category:date

> plotDEGPCA(res, counts = rld, interestingGroups = c("category", "date"), label = TRUE)

Results tables

  • category_als_vs_control_all.csv.gz: All genes, sorted by Ensembl identifier.
  • category_als_vs_control_deg.csv.gz: Genes that pass the alpha (FDR) cutoff.
  • category_als_vs_control_deg_lfc_up.csv.gz: Upregulated DEG; positive log2 fold change.
  • category_als_vs_control_deg_lfc_down.csv.gz: Downregulated DEG; negative log2 fold change.
> saveData(resTbl, dir = data_dir)

DEG tables are sorted by BH-adjusted P value, and contain the following columns:

  • ensgene: Ensembl gene identifier.
  • baseMean: Mean of the normalized counts per gene for all samples.
  • log2FoldChange: log2 fold change.
  • lfcSE: log2 standard error.
  • stat: Wald statistic.
  • pvalue: Walt test P value.
  • padj: BH adjusted Wald test P value (corrected for multiple comparisons; aka FDR).
  • externalGeneName: Ensembl name (a.k.a. symbol).
  • description: Ensembl description.
  • geneBiotype: Ensembl biotype (e.g. protein_coding).

Methods

RNA-seq counts were generated by bcbio and bcbioRNASeq using salmon (Patro et al. 2017). Counts were imported into R using tximport (Soneson, Love, and Robinson 2016) and DESeq2 (Love, Huber, and Anders 2014). Gene annotations were obtained from Ensembl. Plots were generated by ggplot2 (Wickham 2009). Heatmaps were generated by pheatmap (Kolde 2015).
